🐧 Linux Persistence Detection (Command Line)
Linux persistence is largely file-based, relying on scripts that execute during system boot or user login. 
Systemd Services & Timers: Check enabled services and timer files.
systemctl list-unit-files --state=enabled
ls -al /etc/systemd/system/*.service
systemd-analyze unit-paths (to find all service paths)
Cron Jobs & Scheduled Tasks: Inspect scheduled jobs for all users and system-wide.
crontab -l (current user)
crontab -u <user> -l (specific user)
ls -al /etc/cron*
atq (list "at" jobs)
Login & Shell Scripts: Review scripts executed on login.
cat ~/.bashrc, cat ~/.profile, cat ~/.bash_profile
cat /etc/profile, cat /etc/bash.bashrc
ls -al /etc/update-motd.d/ (Message of the Day scripts)
Autorun File Locations (XDG): Check GUI desktop autostart files.
ls -al ~/.config/autostart/
ls -al /root/.config/autostart/
SUID Binaries & Backdoors: Look for files with SUID bits set that can provide root access.
find / -perm -4000 -type f 2>/dev/null
Preload Hijacking: Check for shared libraries loaded before others.
cat /etc/ld.so.preload 


🪟 Windows Persistence Detection (CMD)
Windows persistence heavily utilizes the Registry, Task Scheduler, and Startup folders. 
Registry Run Keys (HKLM & HKCU): Check keys that execute programs on boot or login.
reg query "HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run"
reg query "HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\RunOnce"
reg query "HKLM\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run"
reg query "HKLM\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\RunOnce"
Scheduled Tasks: List all scheduled tasks, focusing on those with suspicious names.
schtasks /query /fo LIST /v
Startup Folders: Check folders containing shortcuts to executables.
dir "%APPDATA%\Microsoft\Windows\Start Menu\Programs\Startup"
dir "C:\ProgramData\Microsoft\Windows\Start Menu\Programs\Startup"
Services: List services that could be abused to run malicious binaries.
wmic service get name,displayname,pathname,startmode | findstr "Auto"
sc query type=service
Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI) Event Consumers: Detect persistent WMI subscriptions.
wmic /NAMESPACE:"\\root\subscription" PATH __EventFilter GET Name,EventNamespace,QueryLanguage
Image File Execution Options (IFEO): Used to trigger debugging processes.
reg query "HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Image File Execution Options" 


1. Comprehensive Check (All Methods)
The AutoRuns PowerShell module (Get-PSAutorun) is the recommended method as it checks registry, services, WMI, and DLL hijacking in one command. 
Command: Get-PSAutorun | Out-GridView
Note: This usually requires installing the module from PowerShell Gallery or using Sysinternals Autoruns. 
2. Scheduled Task Persistence
Scheduled tasks are frequently used to run payloads at startup or login. 
List all tasks: Get-ScheduledTask | Select-Object TaskName, TaskPath, State, Author
List tasks created/modified recently: Get-ScheduledTask | Where-Object {$_.Date -gt (Get-Date).AddDays(-30)}
Check task registration logs: Get-WinEvent -FilterHashtable @{LogName='System';ID=4698} | Format-Table -AutoSize 
3. Registry Run Keys (Most Common) 
Registry keys in the HKLM and HKCU hives are common persistence locations. 
Check HKCU Run Keys: Get-ItemProperty -Path "HKCU:\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run*"
Check HKLM Run Keys: Get-ItemProperty -Path "HKLM:\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run*"
Scan for "Run" keys recursively: Get-ChildItem -Path "HKLM:\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\" -Include "Run", "RunOnce" -Recurse | Get-ItemProperty 
4. Startup Folders 
Files placed in these folders execute on user login. 
User Startup: Get-ChildItem -Path "$env:APPDATA\Microsoft\Windows\Start Menu\Programs\Startup"
System Startup: Get-ChildItem -Path "C:\ProgramData\Microsoft\Windows\Start Menu\Programs\Startup" 
5. Services
List all services: Get-Service | Select-Object Name, DisplayName, Status, StartType
List non-standard services (e.g., not 'System' or 'Disabled'): Get-WmiObject -Class Win32_Service | Where-Object {$_.StartName -notlike "NT AUTHORITY*" -and $_.StartMode -eq "Auto"} | Select-Object Name, PathName, StartName 
6. PowerShell Profile Persistence 
Attackers may modify PowerShell profiles to execute code every time a shell is opened. 
Check User Profile: Test-Path $PROFILE (If true, check content with notepad $PROFILE)
Check AllUsers Profile: Test-Path $PROFILE.AllUsersAllHosts 
7. WMI Event Subscriptions 
List WMI consumers: Get-WMIObject -Namespace root\subscription -Class __EventConsumer
List WMI bindings: Get-WMIObject -Namespace root\subscription -Class __FilterToConsumerBinding 
